<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="20" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="21.[192,1440,1346,1434]" pageId="21" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,302,1346,1370]" pageId="21" pageNumber="20">Ecology</emphasis>
. Lowland, montane, subalpine. Epigean-arboreal. Forests (beech). Shaded ground. Nocturnal; active at night on mossy trees and logs; hides during the day under the loose bark of fallen trees. Gregarious.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[192,1441,1473,1594]" pageId="21" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,298,1473,1497]" pageId="21" pageNumber="20">Biology</emphasis>
. Seasonality: October–March, August. Tenerals: December–March. Predacious (based on mouthpart morphology). Defense mechanism: feigns death when disturbed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[192,1441,1473,1594]" box="[192,1441,1569,1594]" pageId="21" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,411,1569,1594]" pageId="21" pageNumber="20">Dispersal power</emphasis>
. Subapterous (incapable of flight). Moderate runner. Regular climber on trees and logs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[192,1441,1633,1754]" box="[192,896,1633,1658]" pageId="21" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,480,1633,1657]" pageId="21" pageNumber="20">Collecting technique</emphasis>
. Lifting loose bark of fallen trees.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
